  "Question": "<p>According to references (e.g. Wikipedia and elsewhere), the Dirichlet distribution, parametrized by <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_310\"><math alttext=\"\\boldsymbol{\\alpha}=(\\alpha_{1},\\ldots,\\alpha_{K})\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>\ud835\udf36</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub><mi>\u03b1</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2026</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>\u03b1</mi><mi>K</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span>, is <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_311\"><math alttext=\"D(x_{1},\\ldots,x_{K})=\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{B}(\\boldsymbol{\\alpha})}\\prod_{i=1}^{K}% x_{i}^{\\alpha_{i}-1}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>D</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2026</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>K</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>\ud835\udf36</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><msubsup><mo largeop=\"true\" symmetric=\"true\">\u220f</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>K</mi></msubsup><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>i</mi><mrow><msub><mi>\u03b1</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> where <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_312\"><math alttext=\"\\mathrm{B}(\\boldsymbol{\\alpha})=\\frac{\\prod_{i=1}^{K}\\Gamma(\\alpha_{i})}{% \\Gamma\\left(\\sum_{i=1}^{K}\\alpha_{i}\\right)}.\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>\ud835\udf36</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"false\"><msubsup><mo largeop=\"true\" symmetric=\"true\">\u220f</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>K</mi></msubsup></mstyle><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u0393</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub><mi>\u03b1</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u0393</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"false\"><msubsup><mo largeop=\"true\" symmetric=\"true\">\u2211</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>K</mi></msubsup></mstyle><msub><mi>\u03b1</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac></mrow><mo>.</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span> So, if <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_313\"><math alttext=\"K=2\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_314\"><math alttext=\"\\alpha_{1}=\\alpha_{2}=1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>\u03b1</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>\u03b1</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> then this gives <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_315\"><math alttext=\"D(x_{1},x_{2})=1/\\mathrm{B(\\boldsymbol{\\alpha})}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>D</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>\ud835\udf36</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> where <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_316\"><math alttext=\"\\mathrm{B}(\\boldsymbol{\\alpha})=\\Gamma(1)^{2}/\\Gamma(2)=1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>\ud835\udf36</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u0393</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><msup><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u0393</mi></mrow><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> so, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_317\"><math alttext=\"D(x_{1},x_{2})=1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>D</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> for all <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_318\"><math alttext=\"x_{1},x_{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span>.  However, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_319\"><math alttext=\"D(x_{1},x_{2})\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> is defined on the standard <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_320\"><math alttext=\"1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mn>1</mn></semantics></math></span>-simplex defined in <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_321\"><math alttext=\"R^{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></semantics></math></span> by <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_322\"><math alttext=\"x_{i}\\geq 0\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>\u2265</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_323\"><math alttext=\"x_{1}+x_{2}=1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span>.  This is the span (or affine hull) of the two points <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_324\"><math alttext=\"(0,1)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span> and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_325\"><math alttext=\"(1,0)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span>.  Since this is a line segment of length <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_326\"><math alttext=\"\\sqrt{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></semantics></math></span>, the integral of the Dirichlet distribution over this simplex is <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_327\"><math alttext=\"\\sqrt{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></semantics></math></span>, not <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_328\"><math alttext=\"1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mn>1</mn></semantics></math></span> as expected.  What am I missing here?</p> <p>The same problem comes in higher dimensions.  For instance, for <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_329\"><math alttext=\"K=3\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span>, the simplex is a triangle with side <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_330\"><math alttext=\"\\sqrt{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></semantics></math></span>, but the normalization constant becomes <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_331\"><math alttext=\"B(\\boldsymbol{\\alpha})=1/\\Gamma(3)=1/2\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>B</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>\ud835\udf36</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u0393</mi></mrow><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span>, which is not the area of this triangle.</p> <p>What is wrong here?</p>",
  "Title": "Normalizing constant in Dirichlet distribution",
  "Tags": "dirichlet-series"
